# 31.2 Fungal Forms, Nutrition, Reproduction
- 2.2–3.8 million species  
- Unicellular or multicellular  
- Ecological niches: mutualistic, parasitic, free-living  
- Sexual or asexual reproduction  
- Unusual mitosis  
- Specialized absorptive nutrition

---

# Ecological Niches of Fungi

**Mutualistic**  
- Both partners benefit  
- Example: mycorrhizal fungi + plants (nutrients ↔ sugars)

---

**Parasitic**  
- One benefits, the host is harmed  
- Example: *Cordyceps* infecting insects

---

![Cordyceps on insect bg](../Unit1lectures_static/kingdon_fungi/infected_Cordyceps_grasshopper.jpg)

---
![cordyceps on spider bg ](../Unit1lectures_static/kingdon_fungi/1-zombie-jumping-spider-cordyceps-fungus-infection-arons-tiny-safari.jpg)

---

# **Free-living (Saprophytic)**  
- Independent; decompose dead material  
- Example: *Rhizopus* (bread mold) in soil or food

---


![Hyphal growth fit](../Unit1lectures_static/kingdon_fungi/rav38043_3102_hires.jpg)

---

![Mycelium bg](../Unit1lectures_static/kingdon_fungi/rav38043_3103_hires.jpg)

---

# Cell Walls & Mycelium
## - Cell walls contain **chitin** (like arthropods)  
## - Mycelium has high SA:V ratio → rapid nutrient uptake  
## - Fruiting bodies form under stress

---

# Why Fungi Have a High SA:V Ratio
- **SA:V ratio = Surface Area to Volume**  
- Hyphae are long, thin, highly branched → huge surface area  
- More surface = more nutrient absorption  
- Small volume = nutrients travel short distances  

---


![Hyphae bg ](../Unit1lectures_static/kingdon_fungi/rav38043_3104_hires.jpg)

---

# Nuclear Organization
- Monokaryotic (1 nucleus)  
- Dikaryotic (2 nuclei, not fused)  
- Heterokaryotic (genetically distinct nuclei)  
- Homokaryotic (genetically identical)

---

# Mitosis
- Nucleus is unit of division  
- Spindle forms inside nuclear envelope  
- No centrioles (except chytrids)

---

# Hyphae – Vegetative Growth

- **Hyphae** = long, branching filaments of fungal cells  
### - Collectively form the **mycelium**, the main body of the fungus  
### - Role: **growth and nutrient absorption**, not classification  
### - Hyphae can specialize to form reproductive structures (conidiophores, asci, basidia)
  
---


# Conidia – Asexual Spores

- **Conidia** = asexual spores made at the tips of specialized hyphae (*conidiophores*)  
- Especially important in **Ascomycota**  
- Example: *Pseudogymnoascus destructans* (white-nose fungus in bats) spreads via **conidia**  
- Conidia allow **rapid clonal spread**, while sexual structures (like asci) provide genetic recombination

<sub>Conidia are NOT one of the “core four” sexual structures (zoospores, zygosporangia, basidia, asci), but they are central to the ecology of many ascomycetes.</sub>

---

# Reproduction
- Sexual: fusion of haploid hyphae  
- Dikaryotic stage before diploid  
- Fruiting bodies form reproductive structures  
- Four main reproductive structures:  
  - Zoospores  
  - Zygosporangia  
  - Basidia  
  - Asci  



---

# Spores
- Sexual or asexual  
- Dispersed mainly by wind  
- Germinate into new mycelium

---

# 31.3 Fungal Ecology
- Principal decomposers (with bacteria)  
- Break down cellulose and lignin  
- Release C, N, P back into ecosystems


---

# Carnivorous Fungi
##  *Pleurotus ostreatus* paralyzes nematodes


